<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="153" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="153">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="153">
The new species is similar in appearance to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. obatera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obatera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">S. obatera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Wu, 2011 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Striogyia spp., adults and male genitalia, with 8 th sternite: 1, 2. S. simianshana sp. nov., male, holotype; 3, 4. S. obatera Wu, 2011, Prov. Jiangxi, China, genitalia No. WuJ- 325 - 1; 5, 6. S. acuta Wu, 2020, holotype (after Wu 2020) a: phallus, b: male genitalia, c: 8 th sternite. Scale bars: adults, 5 mm; male genitalia, 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.44.64734.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/550666" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">3</figureCitation>
), but can be distinguished from the latter by comparing the antenna, forewing and abdomen. The male antenna of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. simianshana" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simianshana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">S. simianshana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is long, and slightly thicker than that of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. obatera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obatera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">S. obatera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; the postmedial line of the forewing is black and broken, running from the apex to the posterior margin at ca. 1/3 distance from the wing base; the abdomen is dark brown posteriorly. The male antenna of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. obatera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obatera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">S. obatera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is thin; the forewing postmedial line is pale grey and it runs from the apex to the posterior margin at ca. 3/4 from the wing base; the abdomen is yellow posteriorly. The visible difference in appearance between this new species and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. acuta" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">S. acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Striogyia spp., adults and male genitalia, with 8 th sternite: 1, 2. S. simianshana sp. nov., male, holotype; 3, 4. S. obatera Wu, 2011, Prov. Jiangxi, China, genitalia No. WuJ- 325 - 1; 5, 6. S. acuta Wu, 2020, holotype (after Wu 2020) a: phallus, b: male genitalia, c: 8 th sternite. Scale bars: adults, 5 mm; male genitalia, 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.44.64734.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/550666" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">5</figureCitation>
), and other congeners is that the latter have a distinct discal spot or a complete postmedial line on the forewing.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="153">
In the male genitalia, the new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. acuta" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">S. acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Striogyia spp., adults and male genitalia, with 8 th sternite: 1, 2. S. simianshana sp. nov., male, holotype; 3, 4. S. obatera Wu, 2011, Prov. Jiangxi, China, genitalia No. WuJ- 325 - 1; 5, 6. S. acuta Wu, 2020, holotype (after Wu 2020) a: phallus, b: male genitalia, c: 8 th sternite. Scale bars: adults, 5 mm; male genitalia, 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.44.64734.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/550666" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">6</figureCitation>
), but also displays significant differences. In 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. simianshana" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simianshana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">S. simianshana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the apex of the valva is rounded; the paired ox horn-shaped processes are strongly curved outwards, with a broad base; and the plate in the apex of the phallus is nearly triangular (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Striogyia spp., adults and male genitalia, with 8 th sternite: 1, 2. S. simianshana sp. nov., male, holotype; 3, 4. S. obatera Wu, 2011, Prov. Jiangxi, China, genitalia No. WuJ- 325 - 1; 5, 6. S. acuta Wu, 2020, holotype (after Wu 2020) a: phallus, b: male genitalia, c: 8 th sternite. Scale bars: adults, 5 mm; male genitalia, 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.44.64734.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/550666" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">2</figureCitation>
). The valva of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. acuta" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">S. acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is narrower than that of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. simianshana" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simianshana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">S. simianshana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; the pair of processes is only slightly curved outwards, with a narrow base; and the plate in the phallus apex is almost rectangular (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Striogyia spp., adults and male genitalia, with 8 th sternite: 1, 2. S. simianshana sp. nov., male, holotype; 3, 4. S. obatera Wu, 2011, Prov. Jiangxi, China, genitalia No. WuJ- 325 - 1; 5, 6. S. acuta Wu, 2020, holotype (after Wu 2020) a: phallus, b: male genitalia, c: 8 th sternite. Scale bars: adults, 5 mm; male genitalia, 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.44.64734.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/550666" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">6</figureCitation>
). The new species shows visible differences in the male genitalia compared to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. obatera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obatera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">S. obatera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Striogyia spp., adults and male genitalia, with 8 th sternite: 1, 2. S. simianshana sp. nov., male, holotype; 3, 4. S. obatera Wu, 2011, Prov. Jiangxi, China, genitalia No. WuJ- 325 - 1; 5, 6. S. acuta Wu, 2020, holotype (after Wu 2020) a: phallus, b: male genitalia, c: 8 th sternite. Scale bars: adults, 5 mm; male genitalia, 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.44.64734.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/550666" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">4</figureCitation>
) with the apical process of juxta in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. obatera" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obatera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">S. obatera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
being chimney-shaped, while the structures of the other two species are pointed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="153" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="153">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">Male</emphasis>
. (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Striogyia spp., adults and male genitalia, with 8 th sternite: 1, 2. S. simianshana sp. nov., male, holotype; 3, 4. S. obatera Wu, 2011, Prov. Jiangxi, China, genitalia No. WuJ- 325 - 1; 5, 6. S. acuta Wu, 2020, holotype (after Wu 2020) a: phallus, b: male genitalia, c: 8 th sternite. Scale bars: adults, 5 mm; male genitalia, 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.44.64734.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/550666" pageId="0" pageNumber="153">1</figureCitation>
) Forewing length 10 mm; wingspan 22 mm.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/nl.44.64734.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/550666" pageId="0" pageNumber="153" start="Figures 1–6" startId="F1">
